Today’s session focused on evaluating and refining the console-based JDBC mini project. The mentor reviewed the project
implementation and pointed out common mistakes related to database connectivity, SQL query execution, and overall program 
structure. The importance of writing clean, organized, and error-free code was emphasized.

The session highlighted issues such as improper handling of database connections, incorrect SQL syntax, missing validations, 
and poor logic flow. The mentor explained how these mistakes can affect application performance and reliability. Guidance 
was given on how to systematically debug the program by checking each step, including connection setup, query execution, 
and result handling.

During the practical session, I tested different functionalities of the project such as inserting and retrieving data. 
Errors were identified and corrected by improving input validation and fixing logical mistakes in the code. This helped 
in ensuring that the application works correctly and handles user input properly.

The working flow starts by executing the program and testing each functionality step by step. If an error occurs, the 
program is checked to identify whether the issue is in the connection, SQL query, or logic. Corrections are made, and 
the program is tested again. This process continues until the application runs smoothly without errors.

This session is important because debugging and refining are essential steps in software development to ensure the 
application is stable, efficient, and reliable.